Actor Matt Damon criticized U.S. [Immigrations and Customs Enforcement (ICE)](https://www.foxnews.com/category/us/immigration/enforcement) on Tuesday during an interview at the premiere of his new movie and said the agency lacked training.

Attending the Netflix premiere of "The Rip" — his new movie on the streaming platform — Damon wore a "Be Good" pin in protest of the fatal ICE shooting of Renee Good in [Minneapolis](https://www.foxnews.com/category/us/minneapolis-st-paul).

[In a video posted to X](https://x.com/APEntertainment/status/2011529692898099474) by Associated Press Entertainment, Damon explained why he was wearing the pin.

"Yeah, I mean, I think that that incident was incredibly alarming," Damon said. "I think a lot of people are on edge and worried about this and paying very close attention and really worried about this type of behavior out in our streets and the lack of training that we’re reading about and hearing about with some of these people who are going out there."

[**PROTESTERS CLASH WITH FEDERAL OFFICERS AFTER ANOTHER ICE SHOOTING IN MINNEAPOLIS**](https://www.foxnews.com/us/protesters-clash-federal-officers-after-another-ice-shooting-minneapolis)

 ![Matt Damon](https://a57.foxnews.com/static.foxnews.com/foxnews.com/content/uploads/2026/01/1200/675/matt-damon-be-good-the-rip.jpg?ve=1&tl=1)

Matt Damon at Netflix's "The Rip" New York Premiere held at Alice Tully Hall on Jan. 13, 2026, in New York. (Stephanie Augello/Variety via Getty Images)

"Clearly, you know, I’ve heard from a lot of friends in law enforcement that that was not the way they would have handled the situation. I think as concerned citizens, we need to be talking about this and talking about what kind of country we want to live in," Damon continued.

Fox News Digital has reached out to ICE for comment.

[The "Be Good" pins](https://www.foxnews.com/entertainment/celebrity-anti-ice-pins-golden-globes-spark-mixed-reactions-online-after-renee-good-fatal-shooting) were also seen on celebrities at the Golden Globes.

Stars like [Mark Ruffalo](https://www.foxnews.com/category/person/mark-ruffalo), Wanda Sykes, Jean Smart, Ariana Grande, Natasha Lyonne and others wore pins with slogans that read, "Be Good" and "ICE Out."

